<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-06-08T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-06-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1050" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1050">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/4674.</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Brazilian Minister at
                                        Mexico City</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                        State</gloss>.</hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                        <hi rend="italic">Mexico City</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-06-08">
                                        <hi rend="italic">June 8, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>52. In regard to Vice Consul Silliman I do not consider it advisable
                                for him to return to Saltillo for the present as I promised <pb facs="0783" n="667" xml:id="pg_667"/> to Department here that he
                                would stay away from Mexico as long as the present situation would
                                last. The copies desired by Department are being made and will be
                                forwarded by mail in a day or two. Silliman was charged with
                                espionage although no concrete facts were mentioned as I understand.
                                The case seems to have been dismissed.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Cardoso de Oliveira</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>